column168: Our driver was making a delivery of gasoline to the underground storage tank at a convenience store. Driver had stopped the delivery and removed the delivery fitting from the UST so he could gauge tank. After gauging the UST, our driver opened the delivery valve on our cargo tank to add more gasoline to the UST. However, he failed to reconnect the delivery fitting to the UST which allowed about 15 gallons of gasoline to spill onto the concrete and adjacent blacktop. Our driver immediately stopped the flow of gas and covered the area with clay absorbants and spill pads.  Material was swept up and placed in drum for disposal.    Please note as there was no actual "packaging failure", I completed Part III with info that seemed to be appropriate.
Received in HRS as 3 cartons crushed and leaking.  Pallet shifted in transit crushing these containers.

column168: AFTER PICKUP OF WASTE CONTAINERS AT A CUSTOMER'S LOCATION THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE BROKE DOWN AT A LOCAL SHELL GAS STATION.  A WRECKER WAS SUMMONED TO TOW THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE.  UPON ARRIVAL OF THE WRECKER A SMALL AMOUNT OF PAINT WAS NOTICED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE.  APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF LIQUID HAD LEAKED ONTO THE PAVEMENT AND 2 TO 3 GALLONS OF LIQUID HAD SPILLED INSIDE THE TRUCK.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION A 5 GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE LEAKED DURING TRANSIT.  THIS WAS DUE TO IMPROPER SECURING OF THE PALLET WITH SHRINK WRAP AND THE LID OF THE DRUM NOT BEING PROPERLY SECURED.  THE DRIVER OF THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE CLEANED UP THE SPILL WITH ABSORBANT AND OVERPACKED THE LEAKING CONTAINER FOR TRANSPORT AND DISPOSAL.

column168: While unloading gasoline our driver violated established safety procedures by moving the tank truck with the unload lines connected.  In doing so the driver caused a 3" crack in the unload cap and the release of product. The vehicle movement was needed because the driver failed to insure the correct vehicle position before removing any hoses from the unit.   The duraration of the release was approximately 1 minute.  The released product flowed into a storm drain that was clogged with mud which contained the product in that one drain.  The released product was pumped out and the storm drain was flushed by JVR Environmental Services of Spartanburg SC.  The cleanup was completed at 2:30pm (same day)
column169: Immediate meetings with all drivers to review this incident and the need to adhere to all established safety policies and procesdures.

column168: According to the information obtained the following is known.  While the trailer was docked, the driver noticed a release of Sulphuric acid solution at the end of the trailer.  Approximately 600 milliliters released onto the floor of the trailer.  BAX Global, Inc. personnel contained and cleaned up the spill after the release using contents of the spill kit including gloves, and absorbents.  The cleanup materials were placed in the spill kit using a broom and a shovel and placed in the spill kit bucket to be held in the Dangerous Goods bay until disposed. column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, BAX Global, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Forklift operator went to go get his supervisor, because he felt the container was very thin feeling and it would not be safe to move it off the trailer.  Upon further investigation it appears to lower part and bottom of the 55 gallon drum are worn very thin to contain this type of material.  It was decided to attempt to roll the drum off the trailer instead of picking it up with drum clamp device.  Upon doing so the drum caught on a piece of the dock floor which caused a hole in the container.  The drum was placed on its side to avoid any further leakage and proper procedures were taken to clean up the released material.
column169: The driver should have examined the drum prior to initial pick up.  Drivers are our first course of defense when it comes to shipper packages.

Two factors contributed to this incident.  One, a loose lid, two, the shrink/ stretch wrap was very thick and tight around the containers.  Proper clean up procedures were completed by trained personnel.
column169: Packages must be checked by the driver and at every terminal that handles them to assure packaging is in tact and not leaking.

column168: 72 pails were stacked on two skids.  Skids were loaded with too much weight for the skid to bear and the skid allowed the freight to lean into each other chaffing, or denting one container allowing the contents to be released.
column169: We should not accept this type of freight from a shipper.  The driver should request the shipper to break the freight down onto more skids to evenly distribute the weight across several skids.  Shippers do this in an attempt to obtain cheaper freight charges, when in reality we charge by the weight not the amount of room until the shipper takes up over 20' of the trailer.  Drivers need more education on accepting shipper freight.  This is difficult to obtain due to the fact, we do not want to refuse freight nor do we want to upset the customer.  It's a fine line between shipper and carriers.
column172: Plastic container, no capacity or description given

column168: 10, 55 - galon drums on 3 skids.  Too much weight for the skid.  Driver attempted to deliver using hand pallet jack and pallet began to fall apart.  Driver decided to roll them off the already disintegrating skid and attempt clear delivery.  While doing so he feels a nail on the side of the damaged pallet caught 1 of the 55 gallon drums causing a small hole allowign approximately 1 cup to be released.  Just happened the assistant fire chief was visiting this location and assisted in neutralizing the release.  Consignee accepted freight noting damage.
column169: Too much weight on a device made of wood and nails (which are not compatible to begin with) creates a load for disaster.  Shippers who chose to ship hazardous freight should be held accountable and responsible for shipments such as these.  I realize in an effort to cut costs wherever any business can is #1, however, in the end these types of events cost more money and potential damage to property and the environment.  We can't continue putting all the blame on the carrier and the driver---it needs to start at the beginning.  Continuing to put the carrier in the middle, when we are attempting to run a profitable business and expect the driver to attempt to work with the shipper and state that that amount of freight should actually be on 5 skids and not 3, sometimes upset shippers and they will just use someone else.  Shipper training needs to be beefed up and implemented and enforced.

column168: A roll-off box was loaded with a sludgy liquid that had hardened across the top.  Upon transport, a car cut off the truck.  When the driver slammed on his brakes, the load shifted, broke through the crust layer and spill from the roll-off.     The road was closed, and a HazMat crew was dispatched from our Ypsilanti office.  The material hardens upon contact with the atmosphere, so the material was scraped from the road with a Bobcat and was followed by a street sweeper.      Wayne County officials supervised and approved the cleanup.
column169: Improved training for customers and operators.

column168: There was no release. We received a package via Federal Express 8495 5010 0324 that had Boron powder in it. It was packaged in two little foil bags and was marked in Chinese. There were four materials inside the FedEx package and when we ran analysis on the sample, we thought it was Silicon Monoxide, it failed. After the analysis we realized it was Boron metal powder. We beleive Boron metal powder to be a 4.1 when in a fine particle size.
column169: We contacted our agent in China and explained the situation. We are waiting to hear back to see if they agree that the material is a flammable solid. If they agree then all shipments in the future have to be routed through Dangerous Goods Management Burea in Beijing China. This will require them to package the material and ship it correctly.

column168: Upon inspection of the load, the driver noticed it was wet around a couple of drums on the rear of the trailer. He could not identify were the liquid was coming from so he called the Safety dept. I inturn called Soner Environmental Services to respone to the site for evaluation. Sooner called me to inform me that one drum had pressurized and the seam around the bottom was starting to seperate and the drum was weeping. Another drum of the same shpt was pressurized however sooner was able to release the pressure. Sooner secured the drums and contained the weepage and then moved the load to their facility where they overpacked both drums.They cleaned up the few drops of material that got on the asphalt plus they cleaned up the liquid on the trailer floor. Thie waste was manifested and sent to proper disposal. the rest of the load went on to destination without incident. Sooner said the release from the drum was less than 8 gallons and most of it had evaporated due to 100 degree temperature.
column169: This spill was due to packaging and I would recommend the shippers examine the drums closer for fatigue and in extreme warm weather leave more room for expansion.

column168: According to the information obtained the following is known.  While unloading a shipment containing 8 fiber-cardboard boxes, one box that contained one 3.5 liter plastic containers was crushed by a ULD after being placed on top of it by a forklift.  Approximately 2 ounces of product were released onto the warehouse floor.  BAX Global personnel contained the spill and performed cleanup.  BAX Global personnel used a spill kit containing absorbents, and gloves.  The BAX Global personnel placed down absorbents and used gloves to clean up the spill.  The free product, spill kit and damaged package were placed into a 30 gallon drum which will be disposed of internally.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The MSDS was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence. However, BAX Global, Inc. personnel will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Driver had 705 gals of product to transfer from a cargo tank into consignee's storage tank and a 300 gal tote.  The storage tank had 90 gallons of prod in it and the tote was empty before they started. The tank was 700 gal capacity and it had a full line set at 630 gallons. During the unload process the product was to flow into the storage tank and from there into the tote. Our driver shut down and went in to check to see how they were doing. The product level was about 4 1/2" below the full mark on the tank and there was between 125 & 150 gallons in the tote. The driver went back up and restarted unloading at about 10 psi and as soon as he started to unload the storage tank overflowed about 20 gallons. It was discovered that the manhole cover was not on the tank and as a result the last surge of air pushed the product out through it causing the spill.
column169: The plant personnel commented that the spill would not have happened if they had the manhole cover on like they should have.  They replaced the cover.

column168: Shipment checked in to unloading facility with one of four 5-gallon pails leaking.  Spill was contained and cleaned up with absorbent compound (approx 4.5 gallons released).  Spent compound and damaged pail taken to haz mat bay for disposal via environmental contractor.  Inspection of pail revealed small crack approx. .5 inches in length on bottom near the side of the pail.  Several small dimples were also on the bottom of pail, as if it had be struck by something or had been placed on top of some material that caused distortion to the bottom of pail.  Apparently the crack developed in the pail during transport due to this damage.
column169: Notice sent to loading facility to review loading practices and use of dunnage.  Even if there was damage to pail before transport, adequate dunnage under pail very well may have prevented crack from forming.  Remainder of shipment was in good shape and forwarded on to destination.  No other defects in rest of shipment, appears to have been packaged adequately for transport by manufacturer.

column168: At approximately 2:00 pm on July 11, 2006 a tanker trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, (CHES) experienced a minor release of hazardous waste material from a bulk package.  At the time of the release the vehicle was exiting Highway 84 at exit 31 near Bristol Connecticut.  Upon noticing a leak, the driver pulled the vehicle off the main travel section of the highway, set emergency flashers, and proceeded to the rear of the tanker vehicle to investigate the leak.  The driver determined that there was structural failure of the rear valve.  He noticed that the outside casing of the valve has developed a very small hole about one-half of an inch in diameter, and the hazardous material was slowly leaking out.  The tanker truck was carrying Waste Corrosive Liquid, n.o.s. (Nitric Acid Solution 10%) 8, UN 1760, PGIII picked up earlier that day from PraxAir Inc, in Bethlehem, PA.    The driver immediately applied vacuum to the trailer in order to prevent any additional material from leaking out.  He then notified his dispatch of an incident and the emergency contingency plan was activated.  An in-house emergency response crew was dispatched from CHES Bristol, CT service center located about three miles away.      Upon arrival, the emergency response crew placed containment around the rear of the trailer to mitigate any potential environmental contamination.  In addition an appropriate patching material was inserted into the damaged section of the valve to prevent any further release.  Concurrently, CHES notified the CT State police of the incident and the Connecticut Department of Environmental Protection (CT DEP).   State police arrived at the scene shortly after the event and initiated traffic control measures.  The CT DEP had instructed CHES to remain on the scene, take appropriate measures to contain the release, and await the arrival of CT DEP representative.    Due to the small diameter of the valve damage and a short duration of the spill, very small quantity of the material leaked out.    Approximately 1 hour after the initial spill was noted, a representative from CT DEP arrived and assessed the scene.  The representative was satisfied with the emergency response and the temporary repair to the valve assembly.  CT DEP representative took few pH measurements of the surrounding pavement and did not observe any contamination.  The tanker truck was escorted to the CHES Bristol facility to be offloaded.  The material was transported, offloaded and cleaned out without any further incidents.    CT DEP completed an internal report Case No. 2006-04181
column169: Our initial investigation determined that the exterior knife-gate valve was manufactured out of carbon steel and aluminum not stainless steel as the remainder of the valves and the tanker.  Carbon steel is more susceptible to damage by low pH acidic materials.  During the loading process the corrosive solution flowed through this external valve therefore providing extended exposure of the valve to the acidic material.  In addition it was determined that the internal valve, which was manufactured out of stainless steel was not seating properly therefore permitting the material to weep through and rest in the exterior valve housing during the transit.      This tank unit was placed out of service pending the outcome of our investigation.  The exterior damaged portion of the valve will be replaced with an appropriate stainless steel valve, and the internal valve will undergo maintenance and repair if needed.  In addition the tanker will undergo another series of periodic tests prior to being release back into the circulation.      Additionally, all our internal and third party maintenance locations will be re-instructed to recognize the importance of having compatible and appropriate components on the tanker truck vehicles.

column168: While unloading the material at Georgia pacific Resins, INC plant site at Taylorsville, MS, the driver of the unit noticed a wet area on the frame above the dolly legs that had not been there at time of loading. As a precaution, a portable container was placed to catch any leakage, and the trailer was unloaded. After the unloading process was completed, the trailer received an internal wash/purge the external skin and compressed insulation was removed, trailer taken to repair facility for diagnosis and repair (DOT Reg # CT-10030 Collins Tank, Collins, MS).  A 3" crack was discovered in the weld at the number one 3" cleanout port. Weld was repaired, internal inspection and pressure test performed and documented. As a further precaution, additional trailers of the same year/make/model were sent for inspection in order to mimimize and eliminate possibility of recurrence.

column168: Driver had finished transferring product from the cargo tank to customer storage tank.  When he was disconnecting the transfer hose from the trailer, a blast of pressure with product sprayed him, the trailer and the ground around him with product.  Because of the way the driver was standing, product got under his face shield and knocked face shield and hard hat off.  Driver was also wearing safety glasses, a chemical suit and gloves.  Driver did admit that he failed to relieve the pressure in the line before disconnecting.  A plant employee undressed the driver from product covered PPE and placed him in the shower for 15 minutes.  He was taken to hospital and then transferred to a burn unit because of the chemical exposure to his eyes.  He was released the following day.
column169: Driver did not follow disconnecting procedure.  He failed to relieve the pressure first.  He also was not wearing goggles as dictated in his work assignment.  They would have protected his eyes from the product.  Messages went out to all our drivers reminding them that they must wear all their PPE.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Upon opening trailer at the BAX Global Inc. facility, a leak was discovered.  Apparently, the load had shifted in transit, which caused one (1) 5-gallon pail of product to fall from the pallet inside the trailer.  Approximately 2 gallons of free product were released.  BAX Global Inc.personnel containerized the damaged drum into one (1) 55-gallon overpack, and applied oil dry to the free product within the trailer.  Southern Waste Services of Atlanta, Georgia was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival, the free product had soaked into the trailer floor, and no free liquid was recoverable.  Southern Waste Services applied a neutralizing agent to the affected trailer floor.  The one (1) 55-gallon overpack drum was left at the BAX Global Inc. facility pending disposition from the shipper.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to the load shifting in transit, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  BAX Global will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: The leak was discovered inside chemical warehouse at destination and the following actions occurred upon discovery of the leak:  1.  The leak was pre-existing prior to arrival at chemical warehouse;  2.  The truck's floorboard was wet beneath the IBC;  3.  A 6 inch by 6 inch square section of wetted floorboard was removed from the truck and a patch was placed to cover the area from which this small section was removed;  4.  The leak was discovered inside chemical warehouse at destination  5.  IBC was placed in secondary containment immediately upon discovery of leak;  6.  The material that leaked was contained;  7.  The affected areas were decontaminated;  8.  The material in the leaky IBC was transferred to an empty IBC that contained the same material;  9.  The duration of the incident (the following are approximate times):  a.  1141 hours leak discovered and internal emergency response team mobilized;  b.  1145 hours IBC placed in secondary containment and internal emergency response team began initial securing of area, containment and clean-up;  c.  1530 hours contract emergency response team arrived at facility;  d.  1530 - 1830 clean-up completed (approximate 1 gallon of material was intermittantly released over approximately 200 linear feet --);  e.  1830 - 2050 preparation and implementation of transfer of material

Driver arrived to unload product, obtained beginning tank readings for the tank the load was being delivered to. He proceeded to unload. Driver was unaware 2 tanks were manifolded together, and did not check valves on tanks. The product overfilled the other tank. Product ran down side of tank and into the containment area. Driver immediatly shut down pumping, retraced manifold and opened correct valves.

column168: TRAILER WAS BACKED INTO DOCK. WHEN UNLOADER ATTEMPTED TO OPEN THE DOOR, HE COULD NOT DO IT BY HAND, TOO MUCH RESISTANCE. HE THEN USED HIS FORKLIFT TO OPEN THE DOOR. THE UNLOADER DID NOT KNOW A SHEET OF PLYWOOD SHIFTED WHILE THE TRAILER WAS IN   TRANSIT AND WEDGED ITSELF BETWEEN THE TANK AND THE DOOR. SO AS THE DOOR WAS RAISED, THE PLYWOOD CAUSED THE TANK TO FLIP OVER AND THIS DAMAGED THE VALVE ON THE TOP OF THE TANK. THE TANK LEAKED FOR ABOUT ONE HALF HOUR. IT CONTINUED TO LEAK AFTER   IT WAS SET UPRIGHT. AS NITROGEN LEAKED IN A VAPOR FORM, IT EVAPORTATED. HENCE, NO CLEAN UP.

column168: Driver had arrived at the mine site at approximately 9:00 am.  He had donned his PPE and began hooking up the trailer to unload the acid.  Driver was using the consignee's unload hose, which is standard operating procedure.  At approximately 9:15 am, he noticed acid spraying from consignee's hose as proceeded to shut down the unload operation.  The driver was sprayed with acid while attempting to close all valves and cease the operation.  The hose failed at a point approximately halway down the hose.  The hose had been kinked prior to this and weakened at this point.  Subsequent use weakened the hose further until it failed during the unload on 7-22-06.  The spilled acid was contained in a diked-off area and was reclaimed by mine personnel.  The driver used the safety shower to quench the acid on his PPE suit and was taken to the emergency room in Monticello, UT for observation.  He suffered minor burns to his wrist, cheek, neck and ears.  Soda ash and baking soda was used to neutralize the acid on and near the hose.
column169: Drivers and mine personnel will be retrained in observing hoses in use at the mine.  Any hose that is questionable will be placed out of service and properly disposed of.  Better means of storage of the acid hose and more diligence in the use and care of the hoses.  Better means of testing the hoses integrity will be in place.

column168: UPON OPENING THE TRAILER FOR UNLOADING, THE DSR NOTICE THE 1ST PALLET TO COME OFF THE TRAILER WAS A PALLET OF DRUMS. THE FIRST DRUM HAD BLACK LIQUID SPLATTERED INSIDE THE SHRINK WRAP HOLDING THE DRUM IN PLACE AS WELL AS BLACK LIQUID WHICH HAD   COLLECTED ON TOP OF THE DRUM AT THE CAP. CHEM-TEL WAS CALLED TO SEND AN MSDS SHEET AND LARRY FENNELL WAS CALLED TO DETERMINE THE COURSE OF ACTION. SINCE THE DRUM   CONTAINED NITRIC ACID, LARRY DETERMINED THAT AN OUTSIDE VENDOR SHOULD BE CALLED FOR THE CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN-UP. THE TRAILER WAS CLOSED AND PULLED TO THE YARD UNTIL INLAND WATERS ARRIVED. THE TRAILER WAS CHECKED PERIODICALLY. INLAND WATERS   WAS CALLED TO HAVE A TEAM DISPATCHED FOR THE CLEAN-UP. THE TEAM ARRIVED AT THE CONWAY I ROMULUS LOCATION AND THE TRAILER WAS BROUGHT TO A DOCK DOOR. INLAND WATERS SECURED THE AREA WITH CAUTION TAPE, CLEANED THE DRUM AND TRAILER. INLAND WATERS   WAS ASKED TO CHECK ALL OF THE CAPS ON THE DRUMS. THE ONLY CAP THAT WAS LOOSE OR LEAKING WAS ON THE 1ST DRUM AS MENTIONED ABOVE. THE CAP WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH A NEW CAP. THE CLEAN-UP OF THE DRUM AND NEW CAP WAS SUFFICIENT FOR THE FREIGHT TO BE SHIPPED TO THE CUSTOMER, AJAX IN DETROIT. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CAP BY DOM SIMOTA OF INLAND WATERS, IT WAS DETERMINED BY DON THAT THE CAP WAS DEFECTIVE AND DID NOT PERFORM AS NECESSARY TO SECURE THE LIQUID IN THE DRUM. ON THE UNDERSIDE OF THE CAP, THERE IS A ROUND PIECE OF PLASTIC THE DIAMETER OF A PENCIL ERASER JUST BELOW THE RELEASE VALVE IN THE MIDDLE OF THE CAP. THIS PIECE OF PLASTIC WAS PULLED AWAY FROM THE VALVE OPENING EXPOSING A PINHOLE IN THE CAP, WHICH WAS ENOUGH TO ALLOW THE NITRIC ACID TO RELEASE ITSELF FROM THE DRUM. REGARDING THE INJURY DESCRIBED ABOVE, IT WAS MINOR EYE IRRITATION AND HEADACHE TO THE QCL PERSON AT THE SITE OF THE UNLOADING. NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NECESSARY AND THE   EXPOSURE WAS LIMITED TO ABOUT 20 SECONDS.
column169: THIS WAS AN ISOLATED INCIDENT CAUSED BY A DEFECTIVE CAP BEING USED ON THE DRUM.

On July 11, 2006, at approximately 1520 hours, a railway tankcar PLCX 224872, loaded with Styrene Monomer, Stabilized, flammable, UN2055 PG Ill, was reported leaking at the Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) Baton Rouge Louisiana yard. The tank car was discovered leaking from the manway cover, the manway gasket was not correctly installed. The shipper representative responded to the site, installed a new gasket and secured the car. column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases. For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate. By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the sane organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence. After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction. For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be cortacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While at the Flying J Truckstop off Interstate 80, at exit 209 in Rawlins, Wyoming, a leak was discovered coming from the Werner Enterprises trailer.  The Carbon County Fire Department was contacted, and responded to assess the site.  Approximately 1-2 gallons of free liquid was detected on the asphalt lot beneath the trailer.  The Carbon County Fire Department contained the free product prior to contractor arrival.  Rocky Mountain Pump Service was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon inspection of the trailer, it was determined that one (1) 55-gallon steel drum had been punctured by a forklift during loading.  Approximately 15 gallons of free product were released, with the majority contained inside the trailer.  Rocky Mountain Pump Service applied absorbent material to the free liquid inside the trailer.  Rocky Mountain Pump Service proceeded to overpack the damaged drum into one (1) 85-gallon steel recovery drum, along with the spent absorbent material, to be sent on to its destination.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a forklift puncture during loading, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Werner Enterprises will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column169: Since the release was accidental no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence. However, Ecolab, Inc. personnel will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS IN THE RAILYARD, TWO OF THREE CREW MEMBERS ASSIGNED TO A BNSF ROAD SWITCHER REPORTED A STRONG CHEMICAL OR ACRID ODOR. ONE OF THESE CREW MEMBERS REPORTED BECOMING NAUSEOUS WITH ITCHING SKIN ON THE ARMS AND UPPER TORSO. THE LOCAL F.D. WITH EMT’S WERE SUMMONED. THE EMT’S MONITORED THE EMPLOYEE’S HEART RATE, BLOOD PRESSURE, AND BREATHING; AND PROVIDED FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS TO SHOWER AND CHANGE CLOTHES. AFTERWARDS, THE EMPLOYEE REPORTEDLY EXPERIENCED NO FURTHER DISCOMFORT. MEANWHILE, LOCAL OPERATING PERSONNEL INVESTIGATING THE ODOR SOURCE SEARCHED THE RAILYARD AND LATER IDENTIFIED SCMX 2905 AS THE ODOR SOURCE. SCMX 2905 WAS CORDONED OFF IN THE RAILYARD. BNSF MECHANICAL/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDERS APPROACHED SCMX 2905 WITH LITTLE ODOR DETECTABLE. ONCE ATOP SCMX 2905 THE RESPONDERS REPORTED A STRONGER ODOR. INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE LIQUID VALVE HANDLE HAD BEEN REMOVED IN ORDER TO CLOSE THE VALVE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER. THE SEAL ON THE COVER WAS SHELL CHEMICAL 0128932. THE LIQUID VALVE HANDLE PACKING RETAINER NUT ON THE VALVE STEM WAS LOOSE WHICH ALLOWED THE VALVE STEM TO MOVE EASILY AND SOME PRODUCT TO ESCAPE FROM AROUND THE VALVE STEM. RESPONDERS TOOL TIGHTENED THE VALVE STEM NUT ENDING ANY FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE. A VERY SMALL PUDDLE OF PRODUCT HAD GATHERED AROUND THE VALVE AREA AND IT WAS ABSORBED AND CLEANED WITH DISPOSABLE WIPES. AFTERWARDS, RESPONDERS WASHED THE SPILLAGE AREA WITH A BLEACH SOLUTION. NO GROUND IMPACT WAS EVIDENT.   ON 7/26/06, THE EMPLOYEE THAT WAS ALLEGEDLY EXPOSED TO THE PRODUCT ODOR WAS ADMITTED TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL, EXAMINED AND RELEASED AROUND 1700 HRS. CDT. THAT SAME DAY. THIS EMPLOYEE ALSO LOST SEVERAL WORK DAYS THROUGH 8/02/06.
column169: ENSURE SHIPPER’S PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PROCESS IS FULLY IMPLEMENTED AND VALIDATED AS IT RELATES TO THE TOTAL SECUREMENT AND MECHANICAL FITNESS OF ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS.

AFTER REFERRING TO THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET (CLASS 8). THE PKG AND CONTAMINATED MATERIALS WERE TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA BY THE SAME RESPONDER. THE BAG WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE DMP USING THE PROPER HAZ-MAT DISPOSAL PROCEDURE. column168: A BNSF ROAD CREW WAS SETTING OUT A BAD ORDER RAIL CAR IN THE RAILYARD.  ASSISTING THIS CREW ON THE GROUND WAS A BNSF SWITCHMAN AT THE LEAKING END OF THE MOVEMENT.  RCRX 1270, THAT WAS NEXT TO THE BAD ORDER RAILCAR, REPORTEDLY SPLASHED PRODUCT ONTO THE FACE AND INTO THE RIGHT EYE OF THE SWITCHMAN WHEN THE TRAILER MOVEMENT WAS STOPPING.  EXAMINATION AND DIAGNOSIS AT THE LOCAL HOSPITAL EMERGENCY ROOM INDICATED THAT THE SWITCHMAN INCURRED A CORNEAL ABRASION.  TREATMENT INCLUDED AN OVER THE COUNTER EYE DROP SOLUTION AND A PRESCRIPTION PAIN RELIEVER.  THIS EMPLOYEE INCURRED SEVERAL WORK ABSENCE DAYS AFTERWARDS.   A BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDER INSPECTED RCRX 1270 AND FOUND THT THE FILL HOLE COVER WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED. ONE SWINGBOLT WAS NOT APPLIED AND THE OTHER THREE WERE NOT TOOL TIGHT.   RESPONDER PROPERLY SECURED THE FILL HOLE COVER BYTOOL TIGHTENING ALL FOUR COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS BY 0215 HRS.   CDT, 7/7/2006.  THE SMALL AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE ON THE SHELL OF RCRX 1270 WAS NEUTRALIZED AND RCRX 1270 WAS WASHED DOWN AT THE BNSF GALESBURG FACILITY AFTERWARDS.

column168: BNSF SWITCH CREW REPORTED CATX 23154 LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET IN THE RAIL YARD.  BNSF MECHANICAL RESPONDER CLOSED THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (TOBOV) BY 0748 HRS.  CDT, 7/19 THAT STOPPED THE LEAK.  SPILLAGE WAS EVAPORATING FROM THE GROUND IMPACT AREA.  GATX 23154 WAS THEN MOVED OVER DROP CATCH PANS FOR FURTHER OBSERVATION AND INSPECTION.  A BNSF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL/MECHANICAL RESPONDER INSPECTED GATX 23154.  RESPONDER REPORTED THAT THE TOBOV OPERATING ROD HAD OLD INSUFFICIENT PACKING MATERIAL AND THE PACKING GLAND NUT (PGN) WAS NOT TOOL TIGHT.  THE OPERATING ROD WAS LOOSE AND MOST LIKELY HAD VIBRATED OPEN.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP (BOC) WAS 1/4 TURN FROM BEING TOOL TIGHT.  THE CONDITION OF THE BOC GASKET WAS NOT CHECKED.  RESPONDER APPLIED NEW PACKING MATERIAL; TOOL TIGHTENED THE PGN & THE BOC BY 1010 HRS.  CDT, 7/19.  ON 7/27L, A BNSF ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR EXCAVATED THE CONTAMINATED BALLAST AND SOIL FOUND AT THE INCIDENT SITE.  THE EXCAVATED MATERIAL, CLASSIFIED AS A HAZARDOUS WASTE, IS SCHEDULED FOR TRANSPORTATION TO EITHER AN INCINERATION LOCATION OR DISPOSAL AT AN APPROVED LANDFILL SITE.

column168: DURING SWITCHING ACTIVITIES IN THE RAIL YARD, BNSF WATCHMAN REPORTED BEING SPLASHED BY PRODUCT EMANATING FROM PROX 16378.  SWITCHMAN IMMEDIATELY WASHED HIS ARM (CONTACT AREA) WITH NO OTHER FIRST AID REQUIRED AND NO RESULTANT INJURY.  BNSF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND CONTRACT RESPONDERS REPORTED THAT THE FILL HOLE NOZZLE/COVER GASKET WAS OUT OF POSITION WITH THE THREE FILL HOLE SECUREMENT BOLTS BEING TOOL TIGHT.  RESPONDERS REPOSITIONED THE FILL HOLE GASKET AND RESECURED THE FILL HOLE SECUREMENT BOLTS.  CAUSTIC SODA SOLUTION WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE SPILLAGE ON THE TANK SHELL.  SPILLAGE DID NOT IMPACT THE GROUND.  RESPONSE CONCLUDED BY NOON, CDT, 7/19/2006.

column168: BNSF TRAINMASTER REPORTED ACFX 88923 LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP FITTING AREA AFTER ACFX 88923 WAS HUMPED IN THE RAIL YARD.  SPILLAGE ON THE TANK SHELL APPEARED TO BE DRYING TO A WHITE RESIDUE POWDER.  ACFX 88923 WAS CAREFULLY MOVED AND ISOLATED IN THE RAIL YARD.  A BNSF MECHANICAL/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER INSPECTED ACFX 88923 ON 7/24 FINDING NO ACTIVE LEAK SOURCE AND ALL VALVES SECURE.   ACFX 88923 WAS LEFT TO SIT OVERNIGHT.  FURTHER INSPECTION ON THE MORNING OF 7/25 REVEALED THAT ONE OF THE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS NEAR THE MANWAY LID HINGE WAS HANGING OVER THE INNER LIP AND OUT OF POSITION.   THE OLD MANWAY GASKET WAS REMOVED AND A NEW GASKET APPLIED.  THE MANWAY WAS SECURED BY 0830 HRS.  DCT, 7/25/06.  AFTERWARDS, BNSF CONTRACT ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDERS NEUTRALIZED, AND THEN WASHED THE SPILLAGE OFF THE SHELL OF ACFX 88923.  NO GROUND IMPACT WAS REPORTED.    ENSURE SHIPPER’S PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PROCESS IS FULLY IMPLEMENTED AND VALIDATED AS IT RELATES TO THE TOTAL SECUREMENT AND MECHANICAL FITNESS OF ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS.

column168: When driver was unloading the drum at the consignee he used a manual drum cart to do so. When using these this type of manual cart one has to place a hook over the top seam and position two cleats underneath the bottom of the drum. When the operator pulls back on the cart the top hook helps to tip the drum back while forcing the two cleats underneath the drum itself to support it while moving it. When the driver tipped the cart and drum back one of the cleats on the bottom was not lined up properly to go underneath the drum. Instead, the cleat punctured the bottom of the drum contributing to the unintentional release. The drum was removed from the cart and laid on its side to prevent further release and repaired with drum putty. The spilled material was cleaned with absorbent and placed into a recovery container along with the damaged drum.
column169: The driver involved with this release admitted that he failed to check the proper clearances of the cleats before he pulled the drum back. Had he done so he would have noticed that the cleats needed to be repositioned and prevented this unfortnate unintentional release.

column168: A BNSF train derailed its five lead locomotives and eight railcars on the main track at a mainline switch. All rail equipment remained upright. The cause of the derailment was due to the mainline switch being run through previously. Two tank cars of non-odorized propane (GATX 9638 & GATX 9669) were amongst the derailed rail equipment. GATX 9638 derailed upright with all wheels off the rail and GATX 9669 derailed upright with one set of trucks off the rail. Responders from the Big Valley Fire Protection District made the initial assessment that the propane tank cars were intact and not compromised, but lacking the proper gas detection/monitoring sensor equipment, the county sheriff decided to initiate a precautionary evacuation. The evacuation included an estimated 50 people and also closed down a portion of California State Route 299. Vehicle traffic was detoured onto a local thoroughfare (Foothill Road). After the gas sensor equipment arrived, responders confirmed that no propane was leaking from the two derailed tank cars. The evacuation and road closure were lifted around 1700 hrs. PDT, 7/14/06.

column168: P&D Driver picked up freight at shippers and returned to terminal. When the trailer door was opened, smelled the laquer smell. This was the only shipment on the trailer. Noticed one carton discolored and saw floor of trailer was damp - floor of trailr is wooden and the laquer had soaked into the wood. Floor dry was put on the spill area and kept trailer door open and parked away from the dock to dry and air out. Upon inspection of carton, there was no visible damage or crushing. The gallon can inside was intact with lid on and no denting or visible leaks. Leak area shows about mid high on the can, possible pin hole but not visible.
column169: THIS DID NOT LOOK PREVENTABLE AS NOTHING VISIBLE COULD BE SEE TO HAVE CAUSED THE LEAK.

column168: Shipment was loaded on 16514. The shipment relayed through Phoenix. While driver was checking equipment ie noticed paint on the rear of trailer and dolly. Two pails lost the entire contents and the other four were put in an overpack. Approximately 15 gallons were released.
column169: PROPER BLOCKING & BRACING.

column168: AT 18:30 HRS., DURING A ROUTINE YARD INSPECTION AT RADNOR YARD, NASHVILLE TN, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MANAGER JIM BRISKI WAS NOTIFIED OF COVERED HOPPER CGLX 251 LEAKING AT THE CAR SHOP REPAIR FACILITY, FROM ONE OF THE BOTTOM OUTLETS. UPON ARRIVAL HE NOTED LIQUID SODIUM CHLORATE WAS LEAKING FROM THE CAM LOCK CAP ON THE BR SIDE OF THE CAR. THE TOP HATCHES WERE OPENED AND THE A END OF THE CAR WAS EMPTY AND THE B END OF THE CAR WAS 1/4 FULL. THE LOCKING EARS ON THE BR CAM LOCK CAP WERE IN THE OPEN POSITION, ALL OTHER CAM LOCK CAPS HAD WIRE CABLE SEALS. THE EAR COULD NOT BE CLOSED WITHOUT FORCING THEM TO THE LOCKED POSITION. ALL RESIDUE PRODUCT WAS CLEANED FROM THE PIPE AND CAP AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY. THE CAP WAS REPLACED ONTO THE CAR AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. A CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CABLE SEAL WAS APPLIED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK TO SERVICE.     CAUSE CODE 662     NARRI: 5(4-3+0)X(2+0)70

column168: DRIVING A FORKLIFT ON THE DOCK PUNCTURED THE 5-GALLON PAIL WITH THE FORK. HI DRY WAS SPREAD TO CONTAIN THE LIQUID FROM SPREADING TO A WIDER AREA OF THE DOCK. column169: DOCKING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FURTHER FROM THE LOADING AREA OF THE TRAILERS AND BLOCKING AROUND SHIPMENT TO PREVENT ANY FORKLIFTS FROM GETTING CLOSE TO CONTAINERS.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING A PALLET FROM TRAILER 313-6534, DSR(CHRIS NUCKOLLS) NOTICED A LIQUID ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER FROM WHERE HE HAD JUST IT MOVED THE PALLET. THE DSR THEN NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR (CHRIS WILLIAMS) ABOUT THE LEAK. CHRIS WILLIAMS THEN NOTIFIED JEFF TURNER THE AREA SAFTEY SUPERVISOR ABOUT THE SPILL. JEFF THEN INSTRUCTED CHRI TO PROCEED AND NOT TO DELIVER THE DAMAGED PARTS AND TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. CHRIS NUCKOLLS THEN RESTACKED THE PALLET AND DISCOVERED ONE PAIL LEAKING THROUGH A SMALL 1/8 HOLE IN THE SIDE NEAR THE TOP OF THE PAIL. THE HOLE HAD BEEN CAUSED BY ANOTHER PAIL STACKED NEXT TO IT RUBBING AGAINST THE FIRST PAIL. THE TWO PAILS HAD NOT BEEN STACKED EVENLY, CAUSING ONE TO BE HIGHER THAN THE OTHER. WE THEN SEPARATED THE LEAKING PAIL AND ANOTHER PAIL THAT WAS DAMAGED FROM THE REST OF THE SHIPMENT. THE TWO PAILS WERE IN THE MIDDLE OF THE PALLET, SO HANDLING THE FREIGHT DID NOT CAUSE THE HOLE IN THE PAIL. WE THEN DELIVERED THE UNDAMAGED PART OF THE SHIPMENT WITH A DAMAGE/SHORTAGE EXCEPTION. THE SHIPPER WAS THEN NOTIFIED AND ACCEPTED RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE LEAK.
column169: NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER ABOUT THE SPILL. THE SHIPPER STATED THAT THEY WOULD TAKE GREATER CARE WHEN STACKING SHIPMENTS ON PALLETS TO ENSURE THE PAILS ARE THE SAME HEIGHT

column168: When unloading freight from trailer material handler discovered a box that was partially wet and upside down. Apparently, when the box was originally loaded at the shipper it was placed on the floor near the tail end of the trailer. During the course of transportation the box flipped over and as a result one of the inner containers ruptured consequently contributing to the unintentional release. The spilled material was neutralized and cleaned with absorbent and placed into a recovery container along with the damaged box.

On the afternoon of July l4, at approximately 3:00 pm, an employee of the Farmers Cooperative Exchange was loading an Anhydrous Ammonia tank. He was transferring NH3 from the 30,000 gallon storage tank to the 1000 gallon nurse lank. Without thinking, the employee got in the pickup and pulled forward. He had forgotten to unhook the fill hose from the tank. When he pulled away, it broke the liquid valve from the nurse tank, essentially leaving the line from the bulk storage tank open. The Anhydrous Ammonia was leaking from the one-inch fill hose into the air. The employee was able to get away from the area fine, but he was not able to get to the shut-off valve. The general manager of the facility immediately called the Bessie Fire Department. Within about 5 minutes the first fire truck showed up on the scene and began spraying water on the release. The fire department made a couple of attempts to get to the shut-off valve and turn it off, but they were unsuccessful due to the whipping of the hose. The facility is equipped with excess flow valves that are designed to prevent this situation, but the one on this line was not responding. The fire department continued to spray water on the NH3 to try to suppress the flow. We realized that the water from the FD wa3 starting to run off down the railroad track right-of-way. We immediately called in a dozer to contain the runoff water. After 3 1/2 hours of NH3 releasing the FD was finally able to get to the shut-off valve and stop the release. It was approximately 6:30 pm. No one got hurt. We began cleanup by calling in a vacuum truck to come and suck up all the water the FD had sprayed. We stored the water in a 15,000 gallon tank we have at the facility and we also rented a tank from an oilfield company. During the first 30 minutes, the Highway Patrol and Police had shut down a couple small streets in the town of Bessie. They and the FD also evacuated part of the town north of the Coop. We made calls to the LEPC, DEQ, Dept. of Ag. and the NRC to report the accident.   This entire accident could have been avoided if the employee just would have followed the company’s safety procedures that we have in our NH3 Risk Management book. He should have had the tank wheels chocked and should have checked to make sure all hoses and valves where shut off and secure before pulling away. He has had sufficient training and has been working with anhydrous ammonia at Bessie Coop for over 30 years. He just got complacent and didn’t think. In the future, we at Farmers Coop Exchange will be much more cognizant of the company safety procedures and maybe it will prevent anything like this from happening again.

column62: Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Fire, Temperature, or Heat
column168: Our Tractor trailer was travelling at approximately 55 MPH on 1-81 North Bound in the left lane, The driver heard a loud noise and notice that he blew the inside front left axle tire. Our driver then proceed to move into the right lane in order to stop on the shoulder, due to heavy traffic at that time he could not stop safely on the shoulder for about a mile. When he stopped he noticed that the tire was smoking.  He then took his fire extinguisher and tried to put the fire out.  Two other truckers stopped and gave him their fire extinguishers but even with the help of the other two, he was not able to extinguished the fire. Our driver then unhooked his truck from the trailer and called 911. Our driver phoned his employer and was instructed to contact the 24 Hour emergency number provided by the consignor on the Bill of Lading.  When the fire truck arrived at the scene, the fire was burning ONLY around the tires and wheels; the fire had not attacked the trailer floor or sides yet. The fire fighter sprayed water on the surrounding grass and trees. The decision was made by the Fire Marshall to let the trailer burn.  The body of the portable tank containing Sodium Hydrosulfite failed due to extreme heat caused by the fire.
column169: The fire should have been extinguished at the time the fire truck arrived at the scene.  At that time the fire was only around the tires and wheel, not to the body of the trailer yet.  Applying water to this area in order to extinguished the fire would have been no danger, as this product was inside sealed aluminum bins. The trailer floor was not affected by the fire yet and by applying water to the wheels and tires would have been no different than if a trailer was travelling down the road in a rain storm.

column168: A DRIVER FOR SOCI PETROLEUM WAS TRAVELING WEST ON SR 122 WHEN THE DRIVER FELT HIS FRONT STEER TIRE DROP OFF THE EDGE OF THE RIGHT BERM AND ATTEMPTED TO COMPENSATE BACK ON TO THE ROAD AND THEN HE FELT THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRAILER DROPPED OFF AND FELT THE TRUCK WAS JACK KNIFEING AND HE TOUCH THE BRAKE TO STRAIGHTEN IT OUT AND THEN HE STARTED TO FLIP OVER.    THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER ROLLED OVER INTO A SOYBEAN FIELD. THE FRONT COMPARTMENT RIPPED OPEN SPILLING 2709 GALLONS OF #2 LOW SULFUR DIESEL.    THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AND IMMEDIATELY STOPPED ALL TRAFFIC AND THE DRIVER WAS OUT OF TRUCK, BUT WAS INJURED AND HE WAS TAKEN TO THE LOCAL HOSPITAL. THE LOCAL ODOT PUT SAND DOWN ON THE ROAD.     THE EPA, OSHP, DOT, AND PUCO HAZMAT WAS CALLED. ENVIRONMENTAL ENTERPRISE WAS CALLED TO CLEAN THE SPILL IN THE SOYBEAN FIELD. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN THE FIELD.
column169: AFTER OUR ACCIDENT REVIEW, WE FELT THE DRIVER MAY OF BEEN GOING TO FAST FOR THE ROAD, THE DRIVER STATES HE WAS GOING 55 PH, AND THE SPEED LIMIT IS 55. SOCI SAFETY DEPARTMENT FEELS THE DRIVER MAY OF BEEN TRAVELING THE SPEED LIMIT , BUT SHOULD OF BEEN TRAVELING SLOWER. WHEN THE DRIVERS STEER WENT OFF THE BERM AND TRYING TO BRING IT BACK , THE SHIFT OF THE FLUID IN THE COMPARTMENTS CONTRIBUTED TO THE TRAILER ROLLING OVER.    ALL OF OUR DRIVERS HAVE VIEWED A ROLL OVER FILM AND WE FEEL IT MAY BE TIME TO HAVE ALL DRIVERS REVIEW THE FILM AGAIN.

column168: A BNSF train derailed 12 intermodal flatcars ladened with intermodal containers on the main track. The cause of this derailment is under investigation. OOLU 752270 riding atop one derailed flatcar was damaged during the derailment. During staging for lading transfer, two fiberboard cases inside OOLU 752270 were noted with wetness on the sides of the cases. Each case was packed with 4-four liter poly bottles of product and one bottle in each of these two cases were partially crushed during the derailment load shift. These damaged cases were placed in overpacks. Most of the spillage was absorbed by the fiberboard cases and no ground impact was evident. The county sheriff initiated a 1/2 mile precautionary evacuation surrounding the derailment site which impacted between 50-100 people for almost two hours.

column168: A BNSF SWITCH CREW REPORTED UTLX 200594 LEAKING PRODUCT DURING RAILCAR MOVEMENT IN THE RAILYARD. UTLX 200594 WAS CAREFULLY ISOLATED IN THE RAILYARD. LATER THAT MORNING (7/08/06), A SHIPPER RESPONDER ARRIVED AND INSPECTED UTLX 200594. RESPONDER REPORTED THAT THE CONTINUOUS VENT GORTEX MEMBRANE HAD FAILED. THE UPPER PERFORATED PLATE IN THE MEMBRANE RING SUSTAINED AN APPROXIMATE 5 INCH CRACK THROUGH THE CENTER OF THE PLATE. THE GORTEX MEMBRANE UNDERNEATH APPEARED RIPPED IN LINE WITH THE PLATE CRACK. SHIPPER RESPONDER REPLACED THE CONTINUOUS VENT MEMBRANE RING IN KIND. THE RESPONDER ALSO REPORTED FINDING NO SPILLAGE RESIDUE AROUND THE VENT HOUSING OR ON THE SHELL OF UTLX 200594. NO GROUND IMPACT OF PRODUCT SPILLAGE WAS REPORTED. AFTER THE CONTINUOUS VENT MEMBRANE WAS REPLACED AND SECURED, NO FURTHER LEAKAGE WAS EVIDENT DURING SUBSEQUENT MOVEMENT OF UTLX 200594. UTLX 200594 WAS THEN RELEASED TO PROCEED TO ITS DESTINATION.

Superior Driver had hooked up to customer’s unloading line per instructions from the receiver and was given the okay to begin off loading. Discharged product was contained in an engineered containment area and cleaned up in house.

column14: I-20 WEST EXIT RAMP AT GA 70
column168: Vehicle #1 exited from 1—20 West in the right lane of the exit ramp to GA 70. AS Vehicle #1 traveled down the ramp it left the roadway on the north shoulder of the ramp. Vehicle #1 entered the grass and traveled 50 feet before crossing the end of the curb leaving tire marks and tire impressions in the grass and on the curb. As the driver of Vehicle #1 attempted to negotiate the right turn at the end of the ramp, tie load of jet fuel shifted to the left side of the vehicle causing it to overturn onto its left side in the middle northbound lane of GA 70. The vehicle then slid 20 feet across the remaining inside northbound lane of GA 70, striking the center median curb and rolling up onto it’s back and coming to final rest. The tank trailer was damaged as a result of the accident causing approximately 2600 gallons of jet fuel to be released onto the roadway. Appropriate government agencies were notified and a remediation contractor was contracted to clean—up the jet fuel spill according to the state of Georgia environmental standards.

column168: On July 31, 2006, A Huntsman Corp. Shipping Operator was charged with loading a tank truck with Decoupage MNP. Decoupage MNP is a product made in an in-line blend system from Nonyl Phenol and an inhibiter. Decoupage MNP is used in decoupage applications. The truck to be loaded arrived at the 1-luntsman Corp. Conroe Site at 1700 hours to load a shipment of approximately 45,000 lbs of Decoupage MNP. The truck is owned by Heniff Transpo-tation Systems, Inc. This shpment was to be made against our order 55112818. The Shipping Operator lined up the tank and loading equipment to load. He then spotted the truck at the loading site. He performed a preshipment inspection on the truck and approved it to load. The Shipping Operator traced the 2” in diameter loading hose and connected what he thought was the correct hose to the truck. The Shipping Operator then went into the Shipping Office to start the load. The loading operation has a remote pump start in the Shipping Office area. The loading commenced at 1720 hours. At approximately 1755 hours, the Operator went to check to see how the load was progressing. He noticed that the product was flowing to the ground from a different 2” hose than the one he had connected to the truck. He immediately went to the loading site and closed a manual valve to stop the spill. He discovered that he had actually hooked te wrong hose up to the truck. A total of 32,380 lbs of product was lost. The C)perator immediately notified the Utility department who then notified the Lead Operator in Charge. Clean up began immediately. The sewer system was switched to capture the spilled material in our waste water tank and the drainage ditch in the shipping area was diked with sand to prevent material from getting into our treatment ponds. Vacuum trucks were used to remove the product from the diked areas and the product cleaned from the road and other surfaces with soap and high pressure water. All of the liquid material including the soap and water mixture was captured in our waste water tank. The waste water was then shipped off-site for disposal as a class I non-hazardous waste in a deep well. Contaminated soil was placed into three roll-off bins and shipped off-site as a class I non-hazardous waste for disposal in a land-fill. A root cause investigation was performed on 8/2/2006 and action items were developed to prevent a reoccurrence of a similar incident.
column169: Training sessions were held with Shipping Operators to review the incident ar.d to go over good practices. The good practices reviewed included the need to keep hoses untangled so that they can be better traced it was unacceptable to pall on a tangled hose to determine its source, the need to always go back to a loading operation to immediately check to make sure that the line up was correct after starting the loading operation and when working alone, get the truck driver to assist in observing the load if the operator has to leave the area. In the discussion with operators it was emphasized that the remote start could be done against a blocked valve which was the preferred practice. Once the pump was started, the operator could return to the loading area and open the valve thus minimizing the amount spilled if the hook-up was incorrect. Future actions include reviewing whether a pump start switch could be located at the loading rack and to determine if there is some reasonable way to identify the ends of the hose as well as the manifold it is hooked to.

column168: The Con-way driver breaking the trailer upon arrival to the Beaumont facility, advised when he was getting the nose of the trailer that a skid of boxes had fallen off a load table and were on the floor of the trailer. He advised that they were boxes containing paint and that there was not a load bar that should have secured the freight on top of the load table. Upon the driver being able to get to the freight he removed them from the trailer and began to put them into a hazardous containment drum and use absorbal to clean up the spilled product on the trailer floor. The absobal and spilled paint were put into the hazardous contair ment drum with the boxes of spilled paint. 2 small pails in 2 different boxes had been punctured upon falling on the ground of trailer while in transit. During transit the paint was spread over some of the boxes and leaded onto most of the other small pails, but not onto any other freight because when they came off the load table the shrink wrap over the freight acted as a barrier between the hazardous material and other freight loaded on the trailer.
column169: Intercompany spill report was sent and message to supervisor at loading location regarding the failure of proper loading and failure to have shipment properly signed on the trailer by loaded for follow up. Our company continually sends messages to front line managers and supervisors to ensure that our drivers loading and unloading any pails, drums, totes, or any such hazardous material be aware what they are handling and take precaution in the manner they use to load and unload the freight. Continual pregressive discipline will also help in the management of controlling the spills and accidents of this nature.

column168: CARBON DIOXIDE VAPOR WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM A THREADED CONNECTION ON A VENT PIPE EXTERNAL TO THE CARGO TANK. THIS VENT PIPE IS CONNECTED TO THE VAPOR SPACE OF THE CARGO TANK AND LEADS TO A PRESSURE CONTROL REGULATOR WHICH MAINTAINS THE TANK’S PRESSURE WITHIN NORMAL DESIGN LIMITATIONS. VENTING OF CARBON DIOXIDE VAPOR IS PART OF THE NORMAL DESIGN FUNCTIONS; HOWEVER, A THREADED COUPLING NEAR THE INLET TO THE PRESSURE REGULATOR DEVELOPED A “PIN-HOLE” LEAK AT THE THREADS. THE AMOUNT OF CARBON DIOXIDE RELEASED FROM THIS LEAKING FITTING IS ESTIMATED AT LESS THAN ONE POUND. CARBON DIOXIDE GAS IS NOT A REGULATED AIR POLLUTANT AND IS NOT LISTED AS A REGULATED SUBSTANCE UNDER THE EPA RMP, CERCLA, OR OSHA PSM REGULATIONS.
column169: THE THREADED CONNECTION THAT WAS LEAKING HAS BEEN TIGHTENED SO THAT NO LEAKAGE IS OCCURRING IN THE EXTERNAL PIPING ON THE MC 331 CARGO TANK.

column168: Reporting party operates a retail propane operation under the trade name “Pro flame” at the property which it owns located at 4420 McGuire Street in North Las Vegas, Nevada.  On the evening of July 28, 2006, Proflame employee was present at the facility in the ordinary course of his employment. Employee was present at the facility for the purpose of filling approximately one hundred (100) 33-pound forklift motor fuel cylinders for delivery to customers the following day.  Employee was trained and certified by reporting party’s plant operator to fill cylinders as required by Nevada Law.  Employee was dispensing liquid propane gas from a bobtail located at the facility into the forklift motor fuel cylinders. The transfer operation generally involves connecting a brass dispenser nozzle attached to the bobtail truck by a high-pressure rubber hose to the cylinder to be filled. Liquid propane gas is dispensed under pressure into the receptacle cylinder. Employee verified that each of the cylinders was not filled beyond its safe fill level by observing the quality of the gas being emitted from the fixed liquid level gauge located on each of the receptacle cylinders.  The fixed liquid level gauge consists of an aperture into the cylinder which is in turn connected to a dip tube which may be opened through a screw assembly on the gauge itself. The propane escaping through the aperture will change from clear to white as the liquid level in the cylinder reaches the bottom of the dip tube, signaling that the cylinder has been filled to maximum capacity. At that stage, the flow of gas is discontinued to the receptacle cylinder. The fixed liquid level gauge is then closed and the dispenser nozzle is disconnected.  Employee was in the process of filling, by his estimate, approximately the sixtieth of the approximately 100 cylinders at the district at the time of this incident. While filling the cylinder with the fixed liquid level gauge open, gas exiting the gauge ignited from an unknown source and flashed to the cylinder. Reporting party believes the ignition startled an employee, causing him to back away from the cylinder. It is believed that, in that process, the cylinder fell on its side, putting the dip tube attached to the fixed liquid level gauge into the liquid space in the cylinder and allowing liquid propane gas to exit through the oriface. Reporting party believes that ignited gas from the fixed liquid level gauge applied heat to a number of nearby filled aluminum forklift cylinders, causing the safety relief valves installed in each of the cylinders (as required by law) to open, releasing more gas into the atmosphere which was in turn ignited.  Reporting party believes that the fire caused a number of the aluminum cylinders to fail. The fire and failing cylinders caused a number of other cylinders, a bulk storage tank at the premises, as well as at least one storage tank on a bobtail at an adjacent facility operated by Amen gas, to fail.  Reporting
column169: Immediately after this incident occurred, this reporting party arranged for several experts to travel to the scene in an attempt to determine the cause or causes of the incident. Reporting party also fully cooperated with the various federal, state and local agencies involved in the investigation of the incident.  To date, all of the evidence indicates that vaporized propane gas being emitted from the fixed liquid level gauge on the forklift motor fuel cylinder being filled by reporting party's employee,ignited at an unknown source. All of the evidence indicates that this initial ignition set off a chain reaction of events resulting in a large fire and the rupturing of a number of cylinders and two bulk storage tanks.  Reporting party has devoted a great deal of resources to attempting to gain as full an understanding of the cause or causes of this incident as possible. In that regard, the evidence discovered to date indicates that employee was following company procedure and acting in accordance with his training in all respects meaningful to the occurrence of the incident in transfering liquid propane gas into the cylinder being filled.  Reporting party has not discovered any evidence which indicates that there was an unintended release of propane gas or a failure of any equipment which in any way caused or contributed to the incident.  Lastly, reporting party has not discovered any evidence or information which suggests a source of the initial ignition, notwithstanding an exhausting investigation, witness interviews, review of all available physical evidence and consultation with the appropriate federal, state and local authorities.  For the reasons set forth above, reporting party has been unable to formulate any recommendations for the improvement of hazardous materials transportation of relevance or significance to the underlying incident.

column168: Reporting party operates a retail propane operation under the trade name “Pro flame” at the property which it owns located at 4420 McGuire Street in North Las Vegas, Nevada.  On the evening of July 28, 2006, Proflame employee was present at the facility in the ordinary course of his employment. Employee was present at the facility for the purpose of filling approximately one hundred (100) 33-pound forklift motor fuel cylinders for delivery to customers the following day.  Employee was trained and certified by reporting party’s plant operator to fill cylinders as required by Nevada Law.  Employee was dispensing liquid propane gas from a bobtail located at the facility into the forklift motor fuel cylinders. The transfer operation generally involves connecting a brass dispenser nozzle attached to the bobtail truck by a high-pressure rubber hose to the cylinder to be filled. Liquid propane gas is dispensed under pressure into the receptacle cylinder. Employee verified that each of the cylinders was not filled beyond its safe fill level by observing the quality of the gas being emitted from the fixed liquid level gauge located on each of the receptacle cylinders.  The fixed liquid level gauge consists of an aperture into the cylinder which is in turn connected to a dip tube which may be opened through a screw assembly on the gauge itself. The propane escaping through the aperture will change from clear to white as the liquid level in the cylinder reaches the bottom of the dip tube, signaling that the cylinder has been filled to maximum capacity. At that stage, the flow of gas is discontinued to the receptacle cylinder. The fixed liquid level gauge is then closed and the dispenser nozzle is disconnected.  Employee was in the process of filling, by his estimate, approximately the sixtieth of the approximately 100 cylinders at the district at the time of this incident. While filling the cylinder with the fixed liquid level gauge open, gas exiting the gauge ignited from an unknown source and flashed to the cylinder. Reporting party believes the ignition startled an employee, causing him to back away from the cylinder. It is believed that, in that process, the cylinder fell on its side, putting the dip tube attached to the fixed liquid level gauge into the liquid space in the cylinder and allowing liquid propane gas to exit through the oriface. Reporting party believes that ignited gas from the fixed liquid level gauge applied heat to a number of nearby filled aluminum forklift cylinders, causing the safety relief valves installed in each of the cylinders (as required by law) to open, releasing more gas into the atmosphere which was in turn ignited.  Reporting party believes that the fire caused a number of the aluminum cylinders to fail. The fire and failing cylinders caused a number of other cylinders, a bulk storage tank at the premises, as well as at least one storage tank on a bobtail at an adjacent facility operated by Amen gas, to fail.  Reporting
column169: Immediately after this incident occurred, this reporting party arranged for several experts to travel to the scene in an attempt to determine the cause or causes of the incident. Reporting party also fully cooperated with the various federal, state and local agencies involved in the investigation of the incident. column168: ON JULY 24, 2006 AT 5PM IN THE EVENING OUR TRUCK TRAVELING ON HIGHWAY 26 WESTBOUND AT MILE POST 39.5 WAS IN AN ACCIDENT. THE TRUCK WAS TRAVELING ABOUT 50 MPH AS HE CAME OUT OF A CURVE AND HEADED FOR A STRAIGHT STRETCH OF ROAD THE BACK RIGHT TRAILER TIRE CAUGHT THE DITCH. THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO PULL OUT OF THE DITCH HE OVER COMPENSATED CAUSING THE TRAILER TO TURN ONTO ITS SIDE. THE TRAILER WAS THEN DRUG DOWN THE ROADWAY OUT 100 YARDS UNTIL THE TRUCK AND TRAILER UNIT CAME TO A STOP RESTING IN THE MIDDLE OF THE ROADWAY. AS A RESULT OF THE TRAILER BEING DRUG DOWN THE ROADWAY IT WORE A HOLE IN THE SIDE COMPARTMENT OF THE TANK CAUSING PRODUCT TO RELEASE. THE IMMEDIATE NOTIFICATION WAS GIVEN TO EMERGENCY RESPONSE SYSTEM. THE OREGON STATE PATROL, OREGON DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, AND NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WERE NOTIFIED. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ALONG WITH AND ENVIRONMENTAL FIRM WERE ON SCENE TO CLEAN UP AND MITIGATE THE SPILL RESPONSE EFFORT. NO INJURIES OCCURRED ON THE SCENE.
column169: NOTHING COULD HAVE BEEN DONE TO IMPROVE THE PACKAGING OR PROCEDURES TO HELP PREVENT A REOCCURRENCE BECAUSE THE RESPONSIBILITY OF THIS INCIDENT FALLS ON DRIVER ERROR. HOWEVER, WE HAVE AND WILL CONTINUE TO INCREASE OUR DRIVER AWARENESS OF SPEED, AND DEFENSIVE DRIVING TECHNIQUES TO OUR DRIVE TEAM.

column168: THERE WAS NO PACKAGE FAILURE.  A THIRD PARTY TRANSPORTER FINISHED LEADING UNLEADED GASOLINE INTO HIS TRANSPORT TANKER.  HE FAILED TO DISCONNECT THE LOADING HOSES FROM HIS VEHICLE PRIOR TO ATTEMPTING TO DRIVE OFF.  HE SUBSEQUENTLY  PULLED THE LOADING ARM OFF THE RACK CAUSING THE SPILL.    THESE TYPE OF TRUCKS ARE EQUIPED WITH BRAKE INTERLOCKS WHICH KEEP THE BRAKES APPLIED IF THE HOSES ARE CONNECTED. THE VEHICLE'S INTERLOCK SYSTEM DID NOT WORK WHICH ALLOWED THE DRIVER TO ATTEMPT TO LEAVE WITH THE HOSES ATTACHED.
column169: Corrective/investigative Actions   • Action Von Crites: Lock out driver for at least 7 days. (this has been accomplished). Retrain driver on loading rack procedures prior to allowing him to return. Due date: 15 August 2006   • Action Von Crites: Initiate procedures for random inspections of brake interlocks and load fill sensors by terminal personnel. Include all carriers in this program. Due date: 15 August 2006.   • Action Von Crites: Meet with Williams Tank Lines to discuss causes of incident and corrective actions. Williams needs to provide data on preventive maintenance procedures for truck fill sensors and brake interlock systems. Document meeting and Williams actions in a letter to Williams. Due date: 30 August 2006.   • Action Von Crites: Use this incident as a lesson learned in an August safety meeting. Due date: 31 August 2006.

column168: OUR BUSINESS IS AN AGRICULTRUAL COOPERATIVE, WHICH SUPPLIES FERTILIZER AND CHEMICALS TO FARMERS.  ANHYDROUS AMMONIA IS A FORM OF FERTILIZER USED BY OUR CUSTOMERS.  THE PRODUCT WAS IN THE PROCESS  OF BEING APPLIED OUT IN AN AGRICULTURAL FIELD.  THE FIELD WAS LOCATED IN A REMOTE PROTECTED AREA, THE NEAREST FARMSTEAD WAS 2 MILES AWAY.  THE TRANSFER HOSE FROM THE TANK TO THE APPLICATOR APPARENTLY RUBBED AGAINST THE LOCKING CLIP OF THE HITCH PIN AND WEAKENED THE HOSE TO THE POINT THE PRODUCT STARTED TO RELEASE.  THE RELEASE WAS NOT AN ABRUPT RELEASE SO NONE OF SAFETY PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICES ENGAGED.  THE LOCATION OF THE RELEASE WAS PROTECTED BY TREES SO THERE WAS NO WIND TO MOVE VAPOR AWAY FROM AREA, FOR PRODUCER OR LOCATION MANAGER TO SHUT VALVE OFF.  THE PRODUCT DISSIPATED INTO THE AIR, NO ONE WAS INJURED AND NO PRODUCT ENTERED INTO A BODY OF WATER.
column169: MEASURES HAVE BEEN TAKEN TO MAKE SURE THE TRANSFER HOSES DO NOT RUB AGAINST THE APPLICATION EQUIPMENT DURING THE APPLICATION PROCESS.

column168: ONE CASE FOUND DAMAGED WHEN UNLOADED. THE DAMAGED CASE WAS PLACED IN A PLASTIC LINED PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED OVERPACK. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED. THE SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH AMPHOMAG AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

DOCKMAN JOHN STEIER OPENED HIS TRAILER TO BE UNLOADED. HE SMELLED SOMETHING WHEN HE OPENED THE DOOR AND CALLED ME OVER TO SHOW ME A SMALL LEAK COMING FROM THIS SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT WAS A SKID OF PLASTIC PAILS. WE UNWRAPPED THE SHRINKWRAP AND   FOUND THE LEAKING PAIL. IT WAS ON THE BOTTOM AND UP AGAINST A NAIL IN THE SKID. CONTENTS WERE THICK, SO VERY LITTLE LEAKED FROM PAIL. WE TURNED PAIL UPSIDE DOWN AND PUT IT IN A RECOVERY DRUM.
column169: FREIGHT WAS LOADED IN PLASTIC PAILS. WHEN PUTTING ON SKID, SHIPPER SHOULD INSPECT SKID TO MAKE SURE IT IS FREE OF NAILS OR ANY SHARP OBJECT.

Switch crew noted slosh leak form the top of car when car was moved in Chester Yard, at Montgomery, AL. This car was a load of Sodium Aluminate. Mr. Jason Tipton, Terminal Manager, had the car isolated on the North end of the yard. SWS was contacted to inspect the car. Upon SWS’s arrival, they found that the rupture disk was ruptured, and around 1/2 gallon of product had splashed onto the top and side area of the car. SWS found the inspection plug was defective and would not screw into the safety vent. The car was secured to prevent any further spillage, and the outside of the car was cleaned by SWS. The shipper was notified and they contacted GATX repair facility at Mobile, AL. and had a new safety vent installed on the car.   Cause Code - 441   NARRI: 2(5±5+0)X(2+0) = 40

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: CSX train, Q618, reported tank car UTLX8O3 540 leaking from top of car, white cloud reported. This car was located at CSX yard at Pascagoula, MS. Trainmaster Nick Tharp responded to area and located car with heavy odor of LPG in the area. SWS, emergency response contractor dispatched to inspect car, along with Mr. Butch Warden from SWS and Bill Gleason from CSX Hazmat. When SWS arrived at the car, the pressure was taken and found to be 228 lbs. The outage was taken, and “O” outage was found. The pressure relief valve was set at 247.5 lbs. on the car. Chevron was contacted and they agreed to take the car into the plant for off loading. The car was not leaking at this time. 10 buffer cars were placed between the locomotive and the UTLX 803540 and moved to Chevron without further incident. This car was overloaded with Liquefied Petroleum Gas. (Cat Cracker Olefin)   Cause Code - 419   NARRI: 5(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100

column62: Misaligned Material, Component, or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: On Thursday, July 13th at 0840 hours, a CSX Transportation Car Inspector reported that Tank Car GATX71 768 (Load - Flammable Liquid N.O.S.) was releasing vapors in Atlanta's Tilford Yard. CSX Management immediately implemented their emergency response plan and isolated the container. Chemtrec was contacted (Report Number 07132006049) and the shipper, Weyerhaeuser was notified of the non accidental release. SWS was requested to respond and secure the rail car. Investigation reveals that the manway gasket was misaligned and two of eight manway securement bolts/nuts were found less than tool tight. SWS representatives replaced the gasket and properly tightened the manway securement bolts/nuts. After completion, the tank car was released to destination.   NARRI: 5(5±1+0) x (2+0) = 60   Cause Code: 208
column169: ensure employees follow standard operating procedures for securing rail cars prior to releasing for transportation.

During the unloading of trailer 313-9710, DSR Robert Dean found Pro# 605-102960 having damage. Dean informed Bracey Howell, JPW EQS on duty. Howell examined the freight and notice 3 pails dented and 1 of them leaking adhesive. The freight was not dunnaged in the trailer and Pro# 308-518304 was pushed against the freight which caused the damage. Both shipments were loaded by J Lowery from UBI. Howell called Jeff Turner and asked if UPW could deliver the freight to consignee do to the small amount of damage. Turner agreed if the consignee would except. Howell contacted Randy with the consignee. Randy agreed to receive the freight. Freight was delivered with 3 reported damage and 1 leaking can.

column63: UNABLE TO RECOGNIZE DUE TO DAMAGE
column168: When the shipment arrived in Spokane, we found it to be emitting strong odors and to be leaking. The spilled material was recovered and placed in a salvage drum. The outermost box was opened to reveal an inner box that was properly marked and labeled for Dangerous Goods. There were no shipping papers, marking, labeling, emergency response information nor other indicators to lead us to believe the contents were regulated. The FAA was notified, I spoke to SA Joe Derouche. The freight was held pending an FAA inspection.

This shipment was first offered and rejected for improper Dangerous Goods paperwork and markings on 7/25/2006. The shipment was returned to shipper. On 7/27/2006 the shipment was reoffered without any labels, markings, shipping papers, emergency response information nor other indicators to lead us to believe the contents were regulated. You can see where the labels had been affixed, but removed prior to being offered on 7/27/2006. The FAA was notified, I spoke to SAs Rosalind Johnson and Lynette Hurm. The freight is being held pending an FAA inspection.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: AS THE BOXES WERE BEING SORTED WE FOUND THAT TWO OF THE INNER CONTAINERS WERE LEAKING.  THE SPILLED PAINT WAS RECOVERED.  WHEN THE OUTER BOX WAS OPENED, WE FOUND TWO-FOUR LITRE CANS TO HAVE UN 1263  PRINTED ON THEM.  UN 1263 IS THE UN NUMBER FOR PAINT.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED.  I SPOKE TO SA ROBERT CASSIDY.  THE FREIGHT IS BEING HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION IN FRESNO.  THE SHIPPER HAS BEEN NOTIFIED TOO.

column42: DANGEROUS GOODS IN MACHINERY OR DANGEROUS GOODS IN APPARATUS
column168: This shipment was found to be leaking in the FedEx warehouse. Upon inspection of the contents it was found to contain a part suspected to be leaking fuel, later confirmed by the shipper as diesel fuel residue. As the outer package was not offered by the shipper with any dangerous goods markings, labeling, nor with a shipper’s declaration it is believed to be undeclared dangerous goods. FAA agent Jeff Noreika was notified. The package was held pending his investigation.

IT WAS DETERMINED THE TEAK WAS FROM ONE OF 32 55-GALLON DRUMS INSIDE THE CONTAINER. THERE WERE NO SIGNS OF LOAD SHIFT OR OTHER DAMAGE CAUSED TO THE LEAKING DRUM DURING TRANSPORTATION. IT APPEARED THE LEAKING DRUM WAS DAMAGED DURING LOADING OPERATIONS AS IT HAD A SMALL GOUGE IN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM. APPROXIMATELY 40 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER AND WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE CONTAINER ONTO THE FLATCAR. NO PRODUCT WAS RELEASED TO THE 9ROUND. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS OVERPACKED, PRODUCT INSIDE THE CONTAINER WAS NEUTRALIZED AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL APPLIED. THE OUTSIDE OF THE CONTAINER AND FLAT CAR WERE RINSED WITH NEUTRALIZING SOLUTION. THE OVERPACKED LEAKING DRUM, 55-GALLON METAL DRUM OF SPENT PPE AND A 55-GALLON DRUM OF DECONTAMINATION RINSE WATER WERE SECURED INSIDE THE CONTAINER AND IT WAS SEALED WITH SEAL # STN-1 21561.

column168: UPRR’S RESPONSE MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER NOTIFIED LANE A. SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY OF A TANK CAR LEAKING IN THE MASON CITY, IA, NORTH YARD. TGAX 131151 WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. MR. SEKAVEC RESPONDED AND REQUESTED HYDRO KLEAN, ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR, TO RESPOND AS WELL. ONCE HYDRO KLEAN ARRIVED, AN INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED THE FRANGIBLE DISK ON TOP OF THE CAR HAD RUPTURED. HYDRO KLEAN PERSONNEL REMOVED THE BURST DISK AND REPLACED IT WITH A NEW DISK. NO OTHER EXCEPTIONS WERE NOTED WITH THE CAR. AFTER SECURING THE DISK, THE CAR WAS SHAKEN TO INSURE THERE WERE NO OTHER LEAKS. THE CAR WAS THEN SPRAYED WITH A BAKING SODA/WATER SOLUTION TO NEUTRALIZE ANY ACID THAT MIGHT HAVE LANDED ON THE CAR. AFTER THE CAR WAS MOVED, THE AREA BELOW THE CAR WHERE THE ACID LANDED ON THE BALLAST WAS TREATED WITH A BAKING SODA/WATER SOLUTION AS WELL. NO OTHER REMEDIATION IS PLANNED NOR EXPECTED FOR THIS INCIDENT.

column168: Leo Gonzalez entered the Bakersfield Service Center at approximately 1920 on July 28th when I noticed something dripping from the front of his rear trailer. Unit 315- 4072 had a substance leaking from the front of it and since I knew the driver was carrying Hazardous Materials, I immediately had him put the trailer up to the dock. The driver backed the trailer to the dock and i opened the door to see that a tote of Ferrous Chloride was leaking. I walked to the tote ad noticed it was cracked on top and as the trailer was moving, the liquid was gradually splashing through the crack. I inspected the tote and it looked to be weather worn. Realizing this was a Hazardous Materials spill, I contacted my Safety Manager and the manager of the Bakersfield Service Center. I was told to leave the material in the trailer it had arrived in along with the other freight that was already loaded in the trailer because as long as the unit was not moving, the material would not leak out. The trailer was parked and the leaking stopped because the liquid was no longer “sloshing” in the tote.

column168: PPGX 1358 was reported leaking by CSX Transportation employee while the tank car was at the CSX Transportation, South Charleston, WV Railyard. Messrs. Lynn Kerting, AAR-Bureau of Explosives, District Inspector, S. Michael Austin and Timothy Mannas, CSX Transportation Managers-Hazardous Materials Field Services, CSX Transportation inspected PPGX 1358 at 1730 hours. column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: At 0700 hours on Saturday, July 29th a CSX Transportation employee reported smelling “ammonia” odor from tank car GAMX9298 (Residue Last Contained Ammonia, Anhydrous). CSX Management isolated the rail car and contacted Hepaco Environmental to investigate and secure the container. Once on site, Hepaco representatives found the sample line closure plug loose with the valve in the closed position. Teflon tape wAs applied to the closure plug threads. column168: On 07/21/06 at 15:07 hrs, CSXT Train A70712 derailed three cars on the lease track at Chickamauga, TN. Tank car SCMX 4132 was turned over onto its side. column168: Seth Cox, Manager, Train operations, reported he was en route to investigate a reported release from a tank car, which the train crew advised was leaking a small amount of product onto the pavement at the Valla Yard, Yard 60, Track 783, Santa Fe Springs, CA. column168: While performing random tank car inspections with the FRA, GATX 21175, was found to be releasing vapor from the vacuum relief device. Mr. Sekavec attempted to reseat the valve without success. The shipper was contacted to arrange for repair of the car. On Monday, July 31, 2006, a GATX mobile repair unit replaced the defective valve with a new vacuum relief valve. The sealing surfaces of the defective valve were extremely corroded and pitted. The car was released to continue in transportation with the shipper making arrangements to have the car requalified at a later date.

column168: AT 194O HRS ON 7-28-06, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT CHAD CRABTREE, YARDMASTER, LIVONIA, LOUISIANA, HAD REPORTED A LEAKING TANK CAR. BRAKEMAN VERNON ARON HAD REPORTED TANK CAR UTLX 96235 TO BE LEAKING, AND WAS COMPLAINING OF NAUSEA, DIZZINESS, HEAVINESS IN CHEST AND BURNING OF EYES. CAR WAS LOCATED IN BOWL TRACK 33, LINE 16. UPON IDENTIFYING THE CAR, MGR. LERCH CONTACTED DIRECTOR OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS CHARLES SCHIATRE AND ADVISED HIM TO EVACUATE THE IMMEDIATE AREA AROUND THE CAR FOR ... MILE, AND SHUT DOWN OPERATIONS. MGR. LERCH ADVISED RMCC TO MAKE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEM-TREC. MGR. LERCH THEN DISPATCHED UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, UP RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, AND CENTER OF TOXICOLOGY AND ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH, UP AIR MONITORING CONTRACTOR TO THE SITE. ADDITIONALLY, A TOXICOLOGIST WAS CONTACTED FROM CTEH AND PUT IN TOUCH WITH MR. ARON AND MEDICAL PERSONNEL AT THE LADY OF THE LAKE CLINIC IN BATON ROUGE WHERE MR. ARON WAS TAKEN FOR OBSERVATION AND TREATMENT. WHILE ENROUTE TO LIVONIA, LA., MGR. LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE SHIPPER BASF FROM GEISMAR, LA., AND ADVISED THAT A RESPONSE TEAM WAS BEING MOBILIZED TO RESPOND. UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES PERSONNEL INSPECTIED THE CAR AND OBSERVED FROZEN PRODUCT WITHIN THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING, ON SIDE OF CAR, AND A SMALL FROZEN PATCH OF PRODUCT DIRECTLY BELOW THE CAR LADDER. PRODUCT WAS NOTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE SECONDARY SAMPLE LINE NEEDLE VALVE AS BOTH PRIMARY AND SECONDARY SAMPLE LINE NEEDLE VALVES WERE IN THE OPEN POSITION. AFTER DETERMINING SOURCE OF THE RELEASE, BOTH VALVES WERE CLOSED SHUT APPROXIMATELY 1/4-1/2 EACH, WHICH STOPPED THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT. THE PRODUCT WAS THEN ALLOWED TO SUBLIME AND AIR MONITORING WAS CONDUCTED BY BASF PERSONNEL WHO HAD ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 2315 HRS. AFTER THE PRODUCT HAD SUBLIMED, THE SECONDARY SAMPLE LINE NEEDLE VALVE WAS REMOVED, AND A ... INCH PLUG WAS SECURED INTO THE PRIMARY SAMPLE LINE NEEDLE VALVE. THE IMMEDIATE AREA BELOW THE CAR AND SIDE OF THE TANK CAR WAS RINSED WITH WATER BY LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL, AND AT 0145 HRS ON 7-29-06, FULL RAILROAD OPERATIONS RESUMED. CAR ORIGINAL SEAL # BASF1 307066 PROTECTIVE HOUSING. REPLACED WITH BASF 1364763. ON 8-2-06, MGR. LERCH SPOKE TO JOHN STEWART, ETHYLENE OXIDE PRODUCTION LEADER, BASF; GEISMAR, LA. HE INDICATED THAT AN INTERNAL INVESTIGATION WOULD BE CONDUCTED, AND ALL THEIR ETHYLENE OXIDE CARS WOULD BE INSPECTED, AND ANY SECONDARY SAMPLE LINE NEEDLE VALVES WOULD BE REMOVED.
